“You can keep working as if you have a cold,” said Nigara, 19, a maid who asked that her last name be withheld. Often friends and work colleagues are not aware why a woman has taken a few days off, she said.

The risks of complications from clandestine abortions are high, doctors say, increasing the number of women ending up in Kazakh clinics. Many places take women with such problems and just refer obstetric care to Turkmenistan.

In one especially grueling case, E., 24, found herself delivered of a stillborn child after five days of traveling along with more than twenty others in a minibus — a sign of how deeply Turkmenistan relies on Kazakhstan. E. first went to a Kazakh hospital, where she tested positive for syphilis.

“They took us all to a dirty ward somewhere near the morgue,” she recalled. “They treated us at night for five days, because they didn’t want the other people coming in to see us.” She was sent home with black eyes after each battering. “It was the most horrible, awful time,” she said.

Survivors of such abuses often keep details to themselves since the official view is that only suitable and wealthy women can wait for legal birth control.
